
Deployment steps to EKS

1. Confirm the application can be containerized

Make sure the application:
	•	builds successfully
	•	starts successfully as a Docker container
	•	exposes the correct application port
	•	does not depend on local machine files that will not exist in Kubernetes

Files normally needed in the app repo:
	•	Dockerfile
	•	.dockerignore

⸻

2. Build and push the image to private ECR

Build the application image and push it to a private ECR repository.

Result:
	•	you should have an image like:

<AWS_ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.<AWS_REGION>.amazonaws.com/<APP_IMAGE_REPO>:<TAG>

Recommended tags:
	•	immutable tag such as Git commit SHA
	•	optional latest

⸻

3. Identify runtime configuration required by the app

Before deploying to EKS, collect all runtime requirements from:
	•	application config files
	•	currently running server or VM
	•	startup command / service definition
	•	environment variables
	•	external secret sources

You need to know:
	•	application port
	•	active profile
	•	required environment variables
	•	required secrets
	•	database connection details
	•	any external services used by the app

⸻

4. Separate configuration into secrets and non-secrets

Put into Secrets

Use Kubernetes Secret for:
	•	passwords
	•	API tokens
	•	private keys
	•	DB credentials
	•	client secrets

Put into ConfigMap or plain env

Use ConfigMap or normal env values for:
	•	profile name
	•	log level
	•	service URLs
	•	feature flags
	•	port
	•	other non-sensitive config

⸻

5. Confirm database and external dependency access

If the app uses a database or other internal services, verify:
	•	hostnames/endpoints are correct
	•	credentials exist
	•	network connectivity from EKS to those systems is allowed
	•	security groups / firewall rules allow traffic
	•	DNS resolution works from the cluster

This is one of the most common deployment blockers.

⸻

6. Prepare Kubernetes manifests

Normally you need these files.

Required minimum
	•	deployment.yaml
	•	service.yaml

Common additional files
	•	ingress.yaml
	•	hpa.yaml
	•	serviceaccount.yaml
	•	secret.yaml
	•	configmap.yaml
	•	kustomization.yaml

⸻

7. Create the Deployment manifest

The Deployment defines:
	•	container image
	•	replicas
	•	ports
	•	env vars
	•	secret references
	•	resource requests/limits
	•	probes

It should include:
	•	correct image URI
	•	correct container port
	•	correct env variables
	•	readiness probe
	•	liveness probe
	•	resource requests and limits

⸻

8. Create the Service manifest

The Service exposes the pod internally in the cluster.

You need to define:
	•	service port
	•	target port
	•	selector labels

Example logic:
	•	service port = cluster-facing port
	•	targetPort = app container port

⸻

9. Add Ingress only if external access is needed

Create Ingress if the app must be reachable from:
	•	browser
	•	external client
	•	internal HTTP entry point through load balancer

If external access is not needed yet, you can delay this step.

Ingress usually requires:
	•	hostname/path
	•	ingress class
	•	load balancer annotations
	•	TLS/certificate settings if applicable

⸻

10. Add Secrets and ConfigMaps

Create Kubernetes Secret and ConfigMap resources or use your organization’s existing secret mechanism.

Deployment should reference them using:
	•	env
	•	envFrom
	•	secretKeyRef
	•	mounted files if needed

Do not hardcode secret values into Deployment YAML.

⸻

11. Add ServiceAccount and IAM role only if app needs AWS access

If the app must call AWS services such as:
	•	S3
	•	SQS
	•	SNS
	•	Secrets Manager
	•	Parameter Store
	•	DynamoDB

then create:
	•	Kubernetes ServiceAccount
	•	IAM role for service account

If the app does not call AWS APIs directly, this may not be needed.

⸻

12. Add HPA if autoscaling is required

If the application should scale automatically, create an HPA.

This depends on:
	•	CPU or memory thresholds
	•	min replicas
	•	max replicas
	•	resource requests being defined in the Deployment

⸻

13. Organize manifests using base and overlay structure

A common structure is:

app-name/
  base/
    deployment.yaml
    service.yaml
    ingress.yaml
    hpa.yaml
    serviceaccount.yaml
    secret.yaml
    configmap.yaml
    kustomization.yaml
  overlay/
    env-name/
      kustomization.yaml

Base

Contains common reusable resources.

Overlay

Contains environment-specific overrides such as:
	•	image tag
	•	replica count
	•	hostnames
	•	secret names
	•	resource sizing

⸻

14. Update the GitOps / ArgoCD repository

If your cluster is GitOps-managed, do not deploy directly from the app repo.

Instead:
	•	open the GitOps repo
	•	find the application manifest path
	•	update image reference or tag
	•	update required config files
	•	commit the changes

Typical things you update in GitOps:
	•	image URI
	•	image tag
	•	secret references
	•	config values
	•	replica count if needed

⸻

15. Let ArgoCD sync the cluster

Once the GitOps repo is updated:
	•	ArgoCD detects the change
	•	ArgoCD applies the manifests to the cluster
	•	pods are created or updated

If auto-sync is disabled, manual sync may be required.

⸻

16. Verify rollout in Kubernetes

After deployment starts, check:
	•	pods created successfully
	•	image pulled successfully
	•	container starts
	•	readiness probe passes
	•	liveness probe passes
	•	service endpoints created
	•	ingress routes correctly if applicable

⸻

17. Check application logs

If pods fail or restart, inspect:
	•	pod logs
	•	describe output
	•	events
	•	probe failures
	•	crash loop reasons
	•	secret/config resolution errors
	•	DB connection errors

Most first-time failures are due to:
	•	wrong env vars
	•	missing secrets
	•	wrong port
	•	DB/network access failure
	•	bad image tag
	•	startup command mismatch

⸻

18. Validate the application functionally

After pods are healthy, validate:
	•	health endpoint
	•	internal APIs
	•	external APIs if exposed
	•	DB connectivity
	•	dependent service calls
	•	background job execution if applicable

⸻

19. Clean up and standardize

Once deployment works:
	•	remove temporary hardcoding
	•	move non-secret config to ConfigMap
	•	move secret values to proper secret management
	•	use immutable image tags
	•	align folder structure with team standards
	•	document deployment steps

⸻

Minimal practical deployment flow

1. Build app image
2. Push image to private ECR
3. Collect app config and secrets
4. Create Deployment and Service manifests
5. Add Secret / ConfigMap references
6. Update GitOps repo
7. ArgoCD syncs cluster
8. Verify pods, logs, service, ingress

What you need before deployment

At minimum, know these:

1. ECR image URI
2. application port
3. required env vars
4. required secrets
5. database details
6. whether ingress is needed
7. whether AWS access is needed from pod

Current phase mapping

Containerization        -> completed
Image push to ECR       -> completed
Deployment to EKS       -> current phase

